FYI, found that every GET operation causes the following error message in the logs: 

{noformat}
2014-03-20 23:29:10 ERROR 000002141 ReplyQueue               | Failed to identify request context for received error: ExceptionMessage{payload={NullPayload}, context={MULE_CORRELATION_SEQUENCE=-1, MULE_CORRELATION_GROUP_SIZE=-1, MULE_ENCODING=UTF-8, MULE_CORRELATION_ID=1cbd7938-b0c2-11e3-b0a3-477e18de58ac}exception=org.mule.component.ComponentException: Component that caused exception is: DefaultJavaComponent{WalrusReplyQueue.component}. Message payload is of type: NullPayload, componentName='WalrusReplyQueue', endpointUri=vm://WalrusReplyQueue, timeStamp=Thu Mar 20 23:29:10 PDT 2014}
2014-03-20 23:29:10 ERROR 000002141 Contexts                 | com.eucalyptus.context.IllegalContextAccessException: Cannot access context implicitly using lookup(V) when not handling a request.
{noformat}

[~shaon], this is an issue with multipart uploads. I verified it by performing a multipart upload against osg (outside of SC) and tried to retrieve it but encountered the same error. Another data point that confirmed the issue was making the snapshot upload path use normal PUT instead of mpu. The snapshot download worked as expected and I was able to create volumes from snapshots originally created on a different cluster. I've started debugging the mpu issue and will update the ticket accordingly. In the meantime, if you would like to work around this issue to test cross cluster snapshots in particular, you can modify the following property to avoid mpu for snapshot uploads:

{code}
euca-modify-property -p PARTI00.storage.snapshotpartsizeinmb=100000000
{code}
